S3Tools README file
Last update on March 4th 2011


INTRODUCTION
------------

The SKA Simulated Skies (S3) Tools are a set of Python-based routines and interfaces whose purpose is to provide user-friendly access to the SKA Simulated Skies set of simulations, performed at the University of Oxford in the framework of the European Union's SKADS program. The S3 simulations are described on the S3 website (http://s-cubed.physics.ox.ac.uk) and the databases built from these may be queried there. The S3 Tools may then be used on query results to build maps and spectral data cubes. 

In order to use the S3 Tools, you will need a number of python modules : os, sys, getopt, math, numpy, scipy, pyfits, time, random, types, ctypes, stat, Image, Tkinter, tkFileDialog, tkFont, matplotlib. The install script described below first looks for the necessary packages and warns the user if some were not found. Depending on which package is missing, the limitations could go from not being able to build the plots when running tests to downright not being able to make maps at all. For Mac OS X users, the necessary packages should all be included in the SciSoft package (version 2008.3.1 onwards).

If you're reading this, you've successfully downloaded and decompressed the S3Tools.tgz archive, so I do not need to tell you how to do that. Now, to install and run some basic tests of the S3Tools, read on...

1. INSTALLATION 
-------------------------
Installation is made easy by using a python script. Type 

> python install.py 

at the command line prompt and follow the instructions. The script will ask you whether a former installation of the S3Tools exists or not, then prompt you for an installation directory. Depending on your answer to the first question, the script will either fully install the S3Tools in the specified directory, or upgrade the existing installation towards which you've pointed it. 

1.1 Full installation
In that case, the script install.py and all sub-directories (C/,  Config/, Doc/, Jobs/, Output/, Routines/, Tests/ and Tmp/) and the files inside these are copied to the target directory. Then the user is prompted for information regarding the paths to external data (templates, Global Sky Model, etc...) and this information is used to automatically edit the configuration file Config/Config_Path.py, the original Config_Path.py file being moved to Config_Path.py.bak. This configuration can be done manually, as explained in 3.

1.2 Upgrade
Before upgrading, it is wise to backup your installation, at least the Routines/ subdirectory. You probably do not want to backup everything, especially if your Output/ subdirectory is already swollen. 
When upgrading, the script looks through the files inside the Routines/ subdirectory and seeks a file of the same name in the existing installation. If no such file can be found, the file is copied to the target directory. If a corresponding file is found, a diff command is performed on these. If a difference is found, the existing file is backed up with a .py.bak extension and the new one is installed in its place. The script also looks to see if you already have the C/, Tests/ and Jobs/ subdirectories, which are new additions as of March 2011. If not, it creates them and fills them with the relevant files, i.e. C-related files into C/ and symbolic links to the python files in Routines/ into Jobs/. The Tests/ subdirectory is created empty.

1.3 C library
The S3Tools now include a tiny bit of C to speed up some computations. The single C file is S3.c, located under the C/ subdirectory. You need to compile it into a shared object library file called libS3.so. To do so, a typical UNIX command would be 

> gcc -Wall -O2 -fPIC -c S3.c && gcc -shared -Wl,-soname,libS3.so -o libS3.so S3.o

Mac users may need instead to install the free cross-platform make CMake (http://www.cmake.org/) and do a little more work : Instead of the one-liner above, you should use the C subdirectory perform the following steps :

> cd C
> mkdir build
> cd build
> cmake ../
> make

If all went well, you should have a libS3.so under C/build/. 

In either case, you need now just copy that shared library object libS3.so into Routines/ and you should be ready to roll...

2. MANUAL CONFIGURATION 
-------------------------
You may have wanted to skip the automatic configuration done by the install.py script described in 1. In that case, you need to manually edit the Config_Path.py file found under the Config/ subdirectory. For simplicity, we shall assume that the S3Tools were installed in ~/S3Tools/, that is, you have a S3Tools/ directory under your home folder, with subdirectories C/, Config/, Doc/, Jobs/, Output/, Routines/, Tests/ and Tmp/. 

--> NOTE : If you have an older (predating March 2011) installation of the S3Tools, your Config_Path.py *will* be missing a couple lines, which you need inserting. These are :
# Directory where the basic functionality tests are run, and where the reference files are locatedTESTS_DIR=S3TOOLS_PATH+"Tests/"# Directory where the shell script jobs are placed for parallel computingJOBS_DIR=S3TOOLS_PATH+"Jobs/"

2.1 Setting the S3Tools path 
Edit the Config_Path.py file under ~/S3Tools/Config/, so that S3TOOLS_PATH be set to ~/S3Tools/. 

2.2 HI and CO templates [University of Oxford] 
These are templates for the HI and CO emission of galaxies, to use with S3-SAX, made by Danail Obreschkow. To use these :
- Download the SAX_templates.tgz archive from http://www.lra.ens.fr/~levrier/Recherche/S3/ 
- Untar it in a directory of your choice, and edit the Config_Path.py file under ~/S3Tools/Config/, so that SAX_TEMPLATES_DIR be set to that directory. 

--> NOTE : If you have an older (predating March 2011) installation of these templates, you need to create a subdirectory named FITS/ into which FITS files for the templates will be placed. The original template files are ascii (under the ascii/ subdirectory) but they take a while to load into arrays, much longer than when read from FITS files. Consequently, when making SAX cubes, the script first looks for a FITS file, and uses that if it can find it. Otherwise, it uses the ascii file and takes the opportunity to convert it to FITS and save it under FITS/ for future use. The downside of that is that FITS files take up a much bigger disk space than ascii files. 

2.3 HI templates [Kapteyn Institute] 
These are templates for the HI emission of galaxies, to use with S3-SAX, made by Rense Boomsma. To use these :
- Download the KI_templates.tgz archive from http://www.lra.ens.fr/~levrier/Recherche/S3/ 
- Untar it in a directory of your choice, and edit the Config_Path.py file under ~/S3Tools/Config/, so that KAPTEYN_TEMPLATES_DIR be set to that directory. 

2.4 Global Sky Model [MIT] 
This is a model of Galactic emission, made by de Oliveira-Costa et al. (2008). To use it :
- Download the GSM routines and data from the GSM website at http://space.mit.edu/home/angelica/gsm/
- Untar it in a directory of your choice, and edit the Config_Path.py file under ~/S3Tools/Config/, so that GSM_DIR be set to that directory. 
- Replace the gsm.f F77 file in the distribution with a non-interactive one available at http://www.lra.ens.fr/~levrier/Recherche/S3/. Compile that file into a gsm executable, e.g. "g77 gsm.f -o gsm". 

2.5 Epoch of Reionization [IST] 
This is a model of the EoR signal, made by Mario Santos. To use it :
- Download the EoR-Lisbon.tgz archive from http://www.lra.ens.fr/~levrier/Recherche/S3/ 
- Untar it in a directory of your choice, and edit the Config_Path.py file under ~/S3Tools/Config/, so that IST_EOR_TEMPLATES_DIR be set to that directory. 


3. TESTS
-------------------------
The S3Tools installation contains (in the Routines/ subdirectory) a few shell scripts that can be run to test the correct working of the S3Tools (more precisely of SAX_map_script.py and SEX_map_script.py). To use these scripts, you need to download the reference files contained in the archive Tests.tgz (see http://www.lra.ens.fr/~levrier/Recherche/S3/) and untar them in the Tests/ subdirectory of the installation target directory, so that you have a Tests/single-sax.tar.gz file, a Tests/single-sex.tar.gz file and a Tests/Reference/ hierarchy with a number of .fits, .png and .log files, which you may use as references to compare with your runs of the tests script.

3.1 S3-SAX
To test making maps out of S3-SAX, go to the Routines/ subdirectory and simply run

> sh run-SAX-Oxford-tests.sh
and/or
> sh run-SAX-Kapteyn-tests.sh

at the command line prompt. These scripts perform a series of 'python SAX_mapping_script.py' commands with varying arguments, to test the making of HI and CO emission data cubes with various spatial and spectral resolutions. The difference between the two being the templates used, either those made by Danail Obreschkow (University of Oxford), which can be used for both HI and CO, or those made by Rense Boomsma (Kapteyn Institute) for HI only. Obviously, you need to have these installed and the Config_Path.py configured so the scripts can find them (See 3. below)...

The tests performed are the following :
- Spatially unresolved HI emission, with varying spectral resolution, both with and without Gaussian beam smearing
- Spatially resolved HI emission at varying spatial resolutions and constant 120 kHz spectral resolution, both with and without Gaussian beam smearing 
- Spatially unresolved CO emission in the J=1-0 to J=10-9 lines, with spectral resolution varying in proportion to rest frequency, without Gaussian beam smearing
- Spatially resolved (1mas pixels) CO emission in the J=1-0 to J=10-9 lines, with spectral resolution varying in proportion to rest frequency, without Gaussian beam smearing
- Spatially unresolved HI and CO emission in all possible lines, with a frequency coverage from 10 MHz to 200 GHz 
- Spatial window not centered on resolved CO(1-0) emission, with two different shifts- Channel splitting : Using spatially unresolved HI emission with 60 kHz spectral resolution and 6 MHz bandwidth, three cubees are built corresponding to the first 2.4 MHz, the central 1.2 MHz and the upper 2.4 MHz. This is done to check that we recover the same emission as the one we get when bulding the whole 6 MHz cube in one go. This is essential for the correct working of the pseudo-parallel map-making jobs.

These scripts use as an input the single-sax.tar.gz archive, which contains full data for a single galaxy from the S3-SAX database. Some scripts take longer to complete than others, but the data cubes should all be done in a few minutes. They are put in the Tests/ subdirectory and then compared (by the scripts, you do not need to do anything) - using a diff command - to the corresponding files in the Tests/Reference/ subdirectory. If all went well, there should not be any difference found. However, it is possible that small differences could be present (for instance due to different rounding schemes in floating point operations on your machine and on mine...). Therefore, the scripts also build plots of spectra for the different cubes produced and save these plots as .png files in the Tests/ subdirectory. Visual inspection of these plots with respect to the corresponding ones in the Tests/Reference/ subdirectory should make it clear whether there is cause for alarm or not... 

You may build the plots independently of making the FITS files, by running

> python plot-SAX-Oxford-tests.py
or
> python plot-SAX-Kapteyn-tests.py

Actually the shell scripts simply run these commands themselves after having built the FITS files...

3.2 S3-SEX
To test making maps out of S3-SEX, go to the Routines/ subdirectory and simply run

> sh run-SEX-tests.sh

at the command line prompt. These scripts perform a series of 'python SEX_mapping_script.py' commands with varying arguments, to test the making of continuum emission data cubes.

The tests performed are the following :
- Emission with varying spatial resolution both with and without Gaussian beam smearing
- Emission spectra from both lobes and central core of the single test source
- Spatial window splitting : Using spatially resolved (0.1" pixels) continuum emission, four maps are made corresponding to the four quadrants of the source. This is to test that we can split a map in different patches without affecting pixel values.

3.3 Cosmic Microwave Background

To check that CMB emission (simple uniform blackbody emission at T=2.725 K) can be correctly included in the output data cubes, you may run the following shell script

> sh run-CMB-tests.sh

This script builds a cube of unresolved emission centered on the SAX source, covering all HI and CO lines from 10 MHz to 200 GHz, including CMB (i.e. the --nocmb flag has been removed from the calls to SAX_map_script.py), and also a cube of similar size, but on a different patch of sky, which thus recovers only CMB emission. The python script plot-CMB-tests.py which is called by run-CMB-tests.sh then builds a difference cube and checks that correct integrated fluxes are recovered for each line. It also builds a plot of the CMB emission from the CMB-only cube, and overlays the expected curve. Ths plot is saved as cmb_spectrum.png.

3.4 Global Sky Model

To check that the Global Sky Model plugin for the S3Tools works, you may run the following shell script

> sh run-GSM-tests.sh

This script builds 10 single-pixel, single-frequency images at 10, 20, 50, 300 MHz and 1, 2, 20, 30 40 and 50 GHz, centered on a galactic coordinates l=11.3deg and b=89.6 deg, chosen to match those on Fig. 3 in de Oliveira-Costa et al. 2008, MNRAS, 388, 247. The spectrum derived from these (in brightness temperature [K] as a function of frequency [MHz]) is saved into gsm_spectrum.png, which can be directly compared to the aforementioned figure. Also built is a large scale (30 degrees on a side) emission map from the GSM at 1 GHz. This is saved into gsm-30deg-1GHz.fits and a figure of it is saved into gsm_30deg.png. The .png files can be built separately once the FITS files are present under Tests/ by running

> python plot-GSM-tests.py

